# Documentation and code comments

## Documentation

- Keep **all** project documentation accurate when behaviour, versions, remotes, tooling, or standards change.
- Update the README, `docs/**`, `AGENTS.md`, changelogs, and any feature-specific markdown in the same change set when those topics are affected — do not leave stale version numbers, test counts, Node/npm ranges, or archived/outdated guidance.
- Prefer linking to canonical docs (`AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, `docs/readme/*`) rather than duplicating conflicting instructions.
- Document **why** a decision was made when it is non-obvious (for example Nest DI coverage transform, pinned TypeScript 6 vs 7, GOV.UK macro usage).
- After dependency or GOV.UK Frontend upgrades, sync version tables and status sections in README and docs.

## Code comments

- Write **comprehensive comments for future developers**: every public module, class, and non-trivial function should have a clear documentation block describing purpose, inputs/outputs, side effects, and important constraints.
- Explain **why** and **constraints**, not a line-by-line restatement of obvious code.
- Call out security-sensitive behaviour (CSRF, headers, sanitisation), performance traps, and GOV.UK Frontend macro/template requirements.
- Keep Nunjucks templates annotated where macros are composed or where client scripts depend on macro-rendered markup.
- Prefer JSDoc / structured block comments that match existing NestJS style in this repository.
- When changing code, update nearby comments and any related documentation in the same change — never leave comments that contradict the code.

## Agent checklist

When finishing a change:

1. Docs touched or confirmed still accurate for that change
2. Public/complex APIs have up-to-date comments
3. `AGENTS.md` / `.cursor/rules` updated if a standing convention changed
